At the Mercy Of Our Genes
nytimes_articles.abstract:
This summer, in the course of research into my family's genetic history, I traveled into the heart of a largely unmapped landscape: the human genome, the tightly wound coils of DNA that form each one of us. 

     Laid end to end, the coils would form a strand six feet long, bearing data that could fill 13 sets of encyclopedias. Along this strand, only random stretches of DNA, maybe 5 percent of the entire genome, are known to be engaged  in the intricate processes that shape our existence. These isolated DNA bits are the genes. There are an estimated 100,000 or so genes within each one of our cells.

Divorce, New York Style
nytimes_articles.abstract:
Invoking Section 170 of New York State's domestic relations law, each year some 28,000 unhappy husbands and wives bring their marital and family disputes to the New York State Supreme Court. 

     Section 170 speaks of "cruel and inhuman treatment" between spouses. Little did litigants imagine that, as of Jan. 1, they would be subjected to even more such treatment -- this from an unlikely source, the judicial system itself.
